                ðŸ§  If every problem gets kicked back to youâ€¦<br>
                ðŸ§  If the team waits instead of movesâ€¦</p>
                
                <p>â€¦you haven't built a team. You've built a call centerâ€”with you on the other end.</p>
                
                <p>The shift begins with reframing how you train.</p>
                
                <p>Instead of just teaching what to do, teach your team:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Why it matters</li>
                    <li>How to evaluate what's happening</li>
                    <li>What outcomes you're aiming for</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>That's how you move from checklists to champions.</p>

                <h2>Phase 2: Train with a Framework, Not Just a Task List</h2>
                <p>At Day 41 Thrive, we coach leaders to use training frameworks that guide decisionsâ€”not just actions.</p>
                
                <p>One of our favorites: the A.C.T. Model</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>A â€” Assess: What's happening? What's the root of the issue?</li>
                    <li>C â€” Consider: What are my options? Who's affected?</li>
                    <li>T â€” Take Action: What's the best solution with the info I have?</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>Give your team a consistent process to think through problems. Then trust them to act on it.</p>
                
                <p>ðŸ§© When someone misses a delivery deadline<br>
                ðŸ§© When a customer pushes back<br>
                ðŸ§© When a team member calls out sick</p>
                
                <p>They don't have to bring it to you. They know how to think like an ownerâ€”because you taught them how.</p>

                <h2>Phase 3: Shift Responsibility Without Losing Control</h2>
                <p>Leaders get scared to let go because they assume letting go = losing control. It doesn't. Not if you delegate with clarity.</p>
                
                <p>Use outcome-based delegation instead of micro-instructions:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>âœ… Don't say: "Call the supplier and ask if they have it."</li>
                    <li>âœ… Do say: "Make sure we have materials on-site by 10am tomorrow. If they're delayed, find a backup source."</li>
